## Frontend Error Handling

```ts
// In mutation hooks — always in the hook, never in components
const useCreateUser = () => {
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: createUser,
    onSuccess: () => {
      toast.success('User created successfully');
      queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.USERS });
    },
    onError: (error: AxiosError<ApiErrorResponse>) => {
      toast.error(error.response?.data?.message ?? 'Something went wrong');
    },
  });
};
```

Axios interceptor for global error handling:
```ts
api.interceptors.response.use(
  (response) => response,
  (error: AxiosError<ApiErrorResponse>) => {
    if (error.response?.status === 401) {
      // clear auth, redirect to login
    }
    return Promise.reject(error);
  },
);
```

---

## Rules

- Backend: all errors via `ApiError` — never `new Error()` or thrown objects
- Services throw — controllers do not catch
- Global filter handles all exception formatting
- Frontend: mutation errors handled in hook `onError`, never in component
- All API errors show user-friendly toast — never raw error objects to UI
- 401 errors trigger auth logout and redirect

---

## Forbidden (Backend)

❌ `throw new Error('...')`
❌ `throw { status: 400, message: '...' }`
❌ `return null` silently when something is wrong
❌ `try/catch` in controllers to format errors
❌ Exposing internal errors, stack traces, or DB details to client

## Forbidden (Frontend)

❌ `alert()` for error messages
❌ Error handling inside JSX/render functions
❌ Raw error objects displayed to users
❌ Silent API failures with no user feedback
❌ Missing `onError` handler on mutations
